<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,258,1075]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,336,871,895]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word 
<emphasis box="[904,980,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">bifidus</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[988,997,870,895]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">(</emphasis>
bifid) and postfix - 
<emphasis box="[1207,1259,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">ellus</emphasis>
, in reference to the deeply forked uncus in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
